<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920205-0051</DOCNO><DOCID>920205-0051.</DOCID><HL>   Technology:   Glaxo, Imperial Units   Plan to Limit Prices   Of Prescription Drugs</HL><DATE>02/05/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C13</SO><CO>   GLX ICI</CO><MS>BASIC MATERIALS (BSC)CONSUMER NON-CYCLICAL (NCY)</MS><IN>CHEMICALS, PLASTICS (CHM)DRUG MANUFACTURERS (DRG)</IN><RE>DELAWARE (DE)EUROPE (EU)NORTH CAROLINA (NC)NORTH AMERICA (NME)GREAT BRITAIN (UK)UNITED STATES (US)WESTERN EUROPE (WEU)</RE><LP>   NEW YORK -- Two more drug companies said they would limitprices of prescription products in an effort to containhealth care costs.   Glaxo Inc., the U.S. unit of Britain's Glaxo Holdings PLC,said that beginning May 1 it would offer 15% discounts toqualifying federally funded health clinics that serve aboutsix million indigent and elderly people each year.</LP><TEXT>   The discounts will apply to outpatient prescription drugspurchased directly by the clinics for people not covered byMedicaid, but not to programs that already receive Glaxodiscounts. The company estimated that the discounts on theproducts would save the clinics a combined $10 million ayear.   The Glaxo unit, which is based in Research Triangle Park,N.C., also pledged to keep price increases in line with thegeneral inflation rate.   ICI Pharmaceuticals Group, a Wilmington, Del., unit ofImperial Chemical Industries PLC of Britain, said it wouldlimit 1992 price adjustments to the rate of inflation for allproducts to the general public. The company said the maximumprice increase would be 4.1%. A spokesman said the companyalready has an assistance program for people who can showthey're unable to pay for needed drugs.   Last month, Bristol-Myers Squibb Co., New York, whichraised its prescription drug prices twice last year, said itwould give away its heart drugs to patients who couldn'tafford them. And Merck andamp; Co., Rahway, N.J., said it wouldreduce the cost of prescription drugs it sells to certainfederally funded health centers for the poor.</TEXT></DOC>